<div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden">
<div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert wrap-break-word w-full light markdown-new-styling">
<p data-start="54" data-end="94"><span style="font-size: 14pt;"><strong>Pockets</strong></span></p>
<p data-start="107" data-end="138"><strong>Reason for choice of subject</strong></p>
<p data-start="140" data-end="224">• They are {convenient} but can be overlooked by consumers and designers.</p>
<p data-start="231" data-end="258"><strong>Pockets in men’s clothes</strong></p>
<p data-start="260" data-end="558">• Men started to wear {suits} in the 18th century.<br data-start="326" data-end="329">• A {tailor} sewed pockets into the lining of the garments.<br data-start="403" data-end="406">• The wearer could use the pockets for small items.<br data-start="457" data-end="460">• Bigger pockets might be made for men who belonged to a certain type of {profession} .</p>
<p data-start="565" data-end="594"><strong>Pockets in women’s clothes</strong></p>
<p data-start="596" data-end="1246" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">• Women’s pockets were less {visible} than men’s.<br data-start="659" data-end="662">• Women were very concerned about pickpockets.<br data-start="708" data-end="711">• Pockets were produced in pairs using {string|strings} to link them together.<br data-start="796" data-end="799">• Pockets hung from the women’s {waist|waists} under skirts and petticoats.<br data-start="883" data-end="886">• Items such as {perfume} could be reached through a gap in the material.<br data-start="973" data-end="976">• Pockets, of various sizes, stayed inside clothing for many decades.<br data-start="1045" data-end="1048">• When dresses changed shape, hidden pockets had a negative effect on the {image} of women.<br data-start="1155" data-end="1158">• Bags called ‘pockets’ became popular, before women carried a {handbag} .</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
</div>
</div>
