</div>', NULL, 'summary_completion', 'null', 'null', 'null', 'null', '[{"content": "<h3 data-path-to-node=\"2\"><strong data-path-to-node=\"2\" data-index-in-node=\"0\">PART 4: THE HISTORY OF HUMAN MEMORY</strong></h3>\n<p data-path-to-node=\"3\"><strong data-path-to-node=\"3\" data-index-in-node=\"0\">Lecturer:</strong> Good morning everyone. In today''s psychology lecture, I''ll be talking about human memory, and what I want to do first is establish the historical context. So I''ll outline various ideas about human memory and how they''ve changed over time.</p>\n<p data-path-to-node=\"4\">So first, early cultures. Now in the earliest times, let''s say before 3,000 years BC, people were dependent on being able to remember things, perhaps even more than we are today. That''s because <span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">humans could not </span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline; background-color: #f1c40f;\"><strong data-path-to-node=\"4\" data-index-in-node=\"194\">(Q31) write</strong></span>; the skill hadn''t been developed, so a good memory was important. For one thing, it helped people navigate in the area around their homes, and it was the only way to access family history and ancestry. What''s more, a good memory might be the difference between life and death. Most people were hunters and gatherers, so it was essential to understand which foods were poisonous and which were not. <span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"> This was particularly true of </span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline; background-color: #f1c40f;\"><strong data-path-to-node=\"4\" data-index-in-node=\"621\">(Q32) plants</strong></span>, because they sometimes looked very similar, and the only way to store this information and pass it on to the next generation was to remember it. Unfortunately, because it was so long ago, there''s limited information about what techniques we used to assist memory.</p>\n<p data-path-to-node=\"5\">Okay, so moving on now to the ancient Greek